Reasoning: The paper describes an observational study on a professional designer working on a design project in the aerospace industry, focusing on the actions used for the development of a solution to the corresponding problem. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category, as it deals with the interaction between the designer and the design problem. Additionally, the paper discusses the different processes used for problem-solving, which could fall under the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The use of mnesic entities and memory access to develop solutions could also suggest a connection to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also touches on the different abstraction levels used for problem and solution representations, which could relate to the Software Design (cs.SD) sub-category. Finally, the focus on the design of an aerospace artifact could suggest a connection to the Cybernetics (cs.CY) sub-category, which deals with the study of control and communication in systems.
